abstract: A reader urges Mrs. Clinton to stay out of the campaign. Also: Turkey’s nuclear ambitions; President Trump’s foreign policy playbook; the case for regulation.

headline_main: Hillary Clinton’s Attack on Tulsi Gabbard

abstract: Five members of Congress now celebrate the Indian festival of lights with feasts and family gatherings. But some of them think the version on the Hill needs work.
snippet: Five members of Congress now celebrate the Indian festival of lights with feasts and family gatherings. But some of them think the version on the Hill needs work.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — For Representative Pramila Jayapal, there was no better party during her childhood in Jakarta, Indonesia, than the one that took place on Diwali, the Indian festival of lights.

abstract: Party leaders who are fatalistic about Democrats’ chances in 2020 are musing about possible late entrants to the race. Sherrod Brown? Michelle Obama?
snippet: Party leaders who are fatalistic about Democrats’ chances in 2020 are musing about possible late entrants to the race. Sherrod Brown? Michelle Obama?
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When a half-dozen Democratic donors gathered at the Whitby Hotel in Manhattan last week, the dinner began with a discussion of which presidential candidates the contributors liked. But as conversations among influential Democrats often go these days, the meeting quickly evolved into a discussion of who was not in the race — but could be lured in.

abstract: The problem is not just paranoia. It’s also that she questioned a candidate’s motives rather than the soundness of her views.
snippet: The problem is not just paranoia. It’s also that she questioned a candidate’s motives rather than the soundness of her views.
lead_paragraph: On Friday, Hillary Clinton suggested on a podcast that the Russian government might be “grooming” Democratic Representative Tulsi Gabbard of Hawaii as a third-party presidential candidate and referred to the former Green Party candidate Jill Stein as “a Russian asset.”

headline_main: Why Hillary Clinton Shouldn’t Trade in Conspiracy Theories About Tulsi Gabbard

abstract: In a podcast interview this week, the former secretary of state suggested that Ms. Gabbard was being “groomed” to run a third-party presidential campaign.
snippet: In a podcast interview this week, the former secretary of state suggested that Ms. Gabbard was being “groomed” to run a third-party presidential campaign.
lead_paragraph: Hillary Clinton waded into the Democratic primary on Friday by suggesting that Russia was backing Representative Tulsi Gabbard of Hawaii for president and that Republicans were “grooming” her as a third-party candidate.

abstract: We asked veterans of political debates for their reviews of each of the Democratic hopefuls onstage Tuesday.
snippet: We asked veterans of political debates for their reviews of each of the Democratic hopefuls onstage Tuesday.
lead_paragraph: Before Tuesday’s Democratic primary debate, we asked political debate coaches and experts to tell us what each candidate needed to do to have a good night. Here’s that story. Today, we asked the experts how the candidates did.

headline_main: Winners and Losers of the Democratic Debate
byline_original: By The New York Times Opinion

abstract: Biden’s son. Bernie’s heart. Warren’s health plan. Here’s a look at some of the moments that stood out during the debate.

lead_paragraph: Twelve candidates debated for three hours last night, so we can’t blame you if it was hard to keep up. Here is a look at some of the biggest moments.
